⁵ Medi autem et Armenii accessere Libyes] This is the reading of Kritzius and Perizon. on Sanct. Minerv„ lib. 2, 9, note 7. Perizon. reads Libyas, accus. of the Greek form. ΤΙιε first Izi refers to the Libyes, and the latter to the Medi and Armenii, as those two great men have observed.—C.

⁶ Hique mature oppida habuere] Hi, scil. Midi et Armeni. The pronouns hic and is refer sometimes to the more remote antecedent. Quinctil. II. cap. 5, Ut Livium a pueris magis quam Sallustum: et hic (sc. Livius) historiae majoris est auctor. Jug. cap. xvii„ Sed Africam in Europa. Ea finis habet, &c. Hi, in the parenthesis, de- notes the Libyans.—M.

⁷ Quae proxime Carthayinetn Numidia adpellatan] Kritzius reads Quae proxima Carthaginem3 and so Perizon. Quae agrees with the nom. after the verb, scil. Numidia. See Sanct. and Perizon. at lib. 4, c. 12, p. 731, who, after quoting the sentence, says, Sed forte leq. istic appellantur, ut constructio sit, quae loca proxima Carthaginem appellantur Numidia. Appellatur is good Latin. See the note of Cortius. Gronov. in his 3rd Book of observat„ c. 2, p. 444, reads proxime and adpellatur. At the words, Medi autem et Armenii ac- cessere Libyes. Kritzius says, Sallustius accedere, ubi valet se con- ferre ad aliq. semper cum accusat. Conjungit. cf. infra, c. 20, 62, 71, 97 3 but what shall we say of c. 25, where it is followed by ad, quam ocissime ad provinciam accedat ?—C.
